<script>
    import Preview from "$lib/components/Preview.svelte"
</script>

You control every pixel of your interface. You can't control what users upload, type, or paste. User-generated content is the wildcard that breaks beautiful layouts. The only defense is designing defensively.

## What Can Go Wrong Will Go Wrong (Murphy's Law for UIs)

- **Long unbroken strings:** URLs or usernames with no spaces that stretch cards infinitely
- **Missing images:** A profile picture never uploaded, what shows instead?
- **Extremely short content:** A name that's "Jo." A message that's one character.
- **Extremely long content:** A bio that's 3000 words. A title that's 90 characters.
- **Weird characters:** Emoji, right-to-left text, special characters, line breaks mid-word
- **No content:** The user never filled in this field. What does empty look like?

## Defensive Design Rules

- **Clamp text.** Use truncation to limit visible lines. Add "read more" if needed.
- **Set max-widths.** Containers should never grow infinitely.
- **Force word breaks.** Prevent long strings from escaping boxes.
- **Design fallbacks.** No image? Show initials in a colored circle. No title? Design for that.
- **Cap your inputs.** If a username is 30 characters max, enforce it everywhere.

## Defensive Layout

